==Phonological system== The rime dictionaries have been intensively studied as important sources on the [[phonology]] of medieval Chinese, and the system they reveal has been dubbed [[Middle Chinese]]. Since the ''Qieyun'' itself was believed lost until the mid-20th century, most of this work was based on the ''Guangyun''.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=38}}
The books exhaustively list the syllables and give pronunciations, but do not describe the phonology of the language. This was first attempted in the [[rime table]]s, the oldest of which date from the Song dynasty, but which may represent a tradition going back to the late Tang dynasty. Though not quite a phonemic analysis, these tables analysed the syllables of the rime books using lists of initials, finals and other features of the syllable. The initials are further analysed in terms of place and manner of articulation, suggesting inspiration from [[Vyākaraṇa|Indian linguistics]], at that time the most advanced in the world. However the rime tables were compiled some centuries after the ''Qieyun'', and many of its distinctions would have been obscure. [[Edwin Pulleyblank]] treats the rime tables as describing a Late Middle Chinese stage, in contrast to the Early Middle Chinese of the rime dictionaries.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=28–34, 40}}
=== Structural analysis === In his ''Qièyùn kǎo'' (1842), the Cantonese scholar [[Chen Li (scholar)|Chen Li]] set out to identify the initial and final categories underlying the fanqie spellings in the ''Guangyun''. The system was clearly not minimal, employing 452 characters as initial spellers and around 1200 as final spellers. However no character could be used as a speller for itself. Thus, for example,{{sfnp|Baxter|Sagart|2014|p=10}} * 東 was spelled 德 + 紅. * 德 was spelled 多 + 特. * 多 was spelled 德 + 河. From this we may conclude that 東, 德 and 多 must all have had the same initial. By following such chains of equivalences Chen was able to identify categories of equivalent initial spellers, and similarly for the finals. More common segments tended to have the most variants. Words with the same final would rhyme, but a rhyme group might include between one and four finals with different medial glides, as seen in the above table of rhyme groups. The inventory of initials Chen obtained resembled the [[36 initials]] of the rime tables, but with significant differences. In particular the "light lip sounds" and "heavy lip sounds" of the rime tables were not distinguished in the fanqie, while each of the "proper tooth sounds" corresponded to two distinct fanqie initial categories.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|p=28}}{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1984|pp=142–143}}{{sfnp|Malmqvist|1994|pp=19–20}}
Unaware of Chen's work, the Swedish linguist [[Bernard Karlgren]] repeated the analysis identifying the initials and finals in the 1910s.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1984|p=142}} The initials could be divided into two broad types: [[grave and acute|grave initials]] (labials, velars and laryngeals), which combine with all finals, and acute initials (the others), with more restricted distribution.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=59–60}} Like Chen, Karlgren noted that in syllables with grave initials, the finals fell into two broad types, now usually referred to (following [[Edwin Pulleyblank]]) as types A and B.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1984|p=78}} He also noted that these types could be further subdivided into four classes of finals distinguished by the initials with which they could combine. These classes partially correspond to the four rows or "divisions", traditionally numbered I–IV, of the later rime tables. The observed combinations of initials and finals are as follows:{{sfnp|Branner|2006|pp=24–25, 33}}
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align: center;" |+ Co-occurrence of classes of initials and finals in the ''Qieyun'' |- ! rowspan="3" colspan="3" | ! scope="col" colspan="5" | Final class |- ! scope="col" colspan="3" | Type A !! scope="col" colspan="2" | Type B |- style="border-bottom: 2px solid black;" ! scope="col" colspan="2" style="width:12%" | I/IV{{efn|This class is further subdivided in the rime tables between divisions I and IV, but finals of the two subtypes have identical distributions in the ''Qieyun''.{{sfnp|Branner|2000|p=52}}}} ! scope="col" style="width:12%" | II ! scope="col" style="width:12%" | mixed ! scope="col" style="width:12%" | pure III |- ! scope="row" rowspan="8" | Initial<br/>class ! scope="row" | grave ! scope="row" | labials | colspan="2" | yes || yes || yes || yes |- ! scope="row" rowspan="6" | acute ! scope="row" | dentals | colspan="2" | yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | || style="background-color:#ccc;" | || style="background-color:#ccc;" | |- ! scope="row" | retroflex stops | colspan="2" style="background-color:#ccc;" | || yes || yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | |- ! scope="row" | lateral | colspan="2" | yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | || yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | |- ! scope="row" | dental sibilants | colspan="2" | yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | || yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | |- ! scope="row" | retroflex sibilants | colspan="2" style="background-color:#ccc;" | || yes || yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | |- ! scope="row" | palatals | colspan="2" style="background-color:#ccc;" | || style="background-color:#ccc;" | || yes || style="background-color:#ccc;" | |- ! scope="row" | grave ! scope="row" | velars and laryngeals | colspan="2" | yes || yes || yes || yes |- style="border-top: 2px solid black;" ! scope="row" colspan="3" | Rows of the rime tables | style="width:6%" | I || IV || II ||| II–IV || III |} Some of the "mixed" finals are actually pairs of type B finals after grave initials, with two distinct homophone groups for each initial, but a single final after acute initials. These pairs, known as ''[[chongniu]]'', are also marked in the rime tables by splitting them between rows III and IV, but their interpretation remains uncertain. There is also no consensus regarding which final of the pair should be identified with the single final occurring after acute initials.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=75–80}}
=== Reconstructed sound values === Karlgren also sought to determine the phonetic values of the abstract categories yielded by the formal analysis, by comparing the categories of the ''Guangyun'' with other types of evidence, each of which presented their own problems. The Song dynasty rime tables applied a sophisticated featural analysis to the rime books, but were separated from them by centuries of sound change, and some of their categories are difficult to interpret. The so-called [[Sino-Xenic]] pronunciations, readings of Chinese loanwords in Vietnamese, Korean and Japanese, were ancient, but affected by the different phonological structures of those languages. Finally modern [[varieties of Chinese]] provided a wealth of evidence, but often influenced each other as a result of a millennium of migration and political upheavals. After applying a variant of the [[comparative method]] in a subsidiary role to flesh out the rime dictionary evidence, Karlgren believed that he had reconstructed the speech of the Sui-Tang capital [[Chang'an]].{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=24, 34–39}}
Later workers have refined [[Karlgren–Li reconstruction of Middle Chinese|Karlgren's reconstruction]]. The initials of the ''Qieyun'' system are given below with their traditional names and approximate values:{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=45–59}} {| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto;" |- ! rowspan="2" | ! scope="col" colspan="3" | [[stop consonant|Stop]]s and [[affricate consonant|affricate]]s ! scope="col" rowspan="2" | [[Nasal stop|Nasal]]s ! colspan="2" | [[fricative consonant|Fricative]]s ! scope="col" rowspan="2" | [[Approximant]]s |- ! scope="col" | [[Tenuis consonant|Tenuis]] ! scope="col" | [[Aspiration (phonetics)|Aspirate]] ! scope="col" | [[Voice (phonetics)|Voiced]] ! scope="col" | Tenuis ! scope="col" | Voiced |- ! scope="row" | [[Labial consonant|Labials]]{{efn|The rhyme tables describe a later stage in which [[labiodental]] fricatives were also distinguished.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=46–49}}}} | {{tooltip|幫|bāng}} {{IPA|[p]}} | {{tooltip|滂|pāng}} {{IPA|[pʰ]}} | {{tooltip|並|bìng}} {{IPA|[b]}} | {{tooltip|明|míng}} {{IPA|[m]}} | | | |- ! scope="row" | [[Coronal consonant|Dental]]s{{efn|It is not clear whether these had an [[alveolar consonant|alveolar]] or [[dental consonant|dental]] articulation. They are mostly alveolar in modern Chinese varieties.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=49}}}} | {{tooltip|端|duān}} {{IPA|[t]}} | {{tooltip|透|tòu}} {{IPA|[tʰ]}} | {{tooltip|定|dìng}} {{IPA|[d]}} | {{tooltip|泥|ní}} {{IPA|[n]}} | | | |- ! scope="row" | [[retroflex consonant|Retroflex stop]]s{{efn|Karlgren reconstructed these as palatal stops, but most scholars now believe they were retroflex stops.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=50}}}} | {{tooltip|知|zhī}} {{IPA|[ʈ]}} | {{tooltip|徹|chè}} {{IPA|[ʈʰ]}} | {{tooltip|澄|chéng}} {{IPA|[ɖ]}} | {{tooltip|娘|niáng}} {{IPA|[ɳ]}} | | | |- ! scope="row" | [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]] | | | | | | | align="center" | {{tooltip|來|lái}} {{IPA|[l]}} |- ! scope="row" | [[Affricate consonant|Dental sibilant]]s | {{tooltip|精|jīng}} {{IPA|[ts]}} | {{tooltip|清|qīng}} {{IPA|[tsʰ]}} | {{tooltip|從|cóng}} {{IPA|[dz]}} | | {{tooltip|心|xīn}} {{IPA|[s]}} | {{tooltip|邪|xié}} {{IPA|[z]}} | |- ! scope="row" | Retroflex sibilants | {{tooltip|莊|zhuāng}} {{IPA|[tʂ]}} | {{tooltip|初|chū}} {{IPA|[tʂʰ]}} | {{tooltip|崇|chóng}} {{IPA|[dʐ]}} | | {{tooltip|生|shēng}} {{IPA|[ʂ]}} | {{tooltip|俟|sì}} {{IPA|[ʐ]}}{{efn|The {{IPA|[ʐ]}} initial occurs in only two words {{linktext|俟}} and {{linktext|漦}} in the ''Qieyun'', and is merged with {{IPA|[dʐ]}} in the ''[[Guangyun]]''. It is omitted in many reconstructions, and has no standard Chinese name.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=56–57, 206}}}} | |- ! scope="row" | [[alveolo-palatal consonant|Palatal]]s{{efn|The retroflex and palatal sibilants were treated as a single series in the rime tables. Chen Li was the first to realize (in 1842) that they were distinguished in the ''Qieyun''.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=54–55}}}} | {{tooltip|章|zhāng}} {{IPA|[tɕ]}} | {{tooltip|昌|chāng}} {{IPA|[tɕʰ]}} | {{tooltip|禪|chán}} {{IPA|[dʑ]}}{{efn|The initials 禪 and 船 are reversed from their positions in the rime tables, which are believed to have confused them.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=52–54}}|name="dzr"}} | {{tooltip|日|rì}} {{IPA|[ɲ]}} | {{tooltip|書|shū}} {{IPA|[ɕ]}} | {{tooltip|船|chuán}} {{IPA|[ʑ]}}{{efn|name="dzr"}} | align="center" | {{tooltip|以|yǐ}} {{IPA|[j]}}{{efn|In the rime tables, the palatal allophone of {{IPA|[ɣ]}} (云) is combined with {{IPA|[j]}} (以) as a single laryngeal initial 喻. However in the ''Qieyun'' system {{IPA|[j]}} patterns with the palatals.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=55–56, 59}}|name="palatal"}} |- ! scope="row" | [[Velar consonant|Velar]]s | {{tooltip|見|jiàn}} {{IPA|[k]}} | {{tooltip|溪|xī}} {{IPA|[kʰ]}} | {{tooltip|群|qún}} {{IPA|[ɡ]}} | {{tooltip|疑|yí}} {{IPA|[ŋ]}} | | | |- ! scope="row" | [[Glottal consonant|Laryngeal]]s{{efn|The point of articulation of the fricatives is not clear, and varies between the modern varieties.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|p=58}}}} | {{tooltip|影|yǐng}} {{IPA|[ʔ]}} | | | | {{tooltip|曉|xiǎo}} {{IPA|[x]}} | {{tooltip|匣|xiá}}/{{tooltip|云|yún}} {{IPA|[ɣ]}}{{efn|name="palatal"}} | |}
In most cases, the simpler inventories of initials of modern varieties of Chinese can be treated as varying developments of the ''Qieyun'' initials. The voicing distinction is retained in [[Wu Chinese]] dialects, but has disappeared from other varieties. Except in the [[Min Chinese]] dialects, a [[labiodental]] series has split from the labial series, a development already reflected in the Song dynasty rime tables. The retroflex and palatal sibilants had also merged by that time. In Min dialects the retroflex stops have merged with the dental stops, while elsewhere they have merged with the retroflex sibilants. In the south these have also merged with the dental sibilants, but the distinction is maintained in most [[Mandarin Chinese]] dialects. The palatal series of modern Mandarin dialects, resulting from a merger of palatal allophones of dental sibilants and velars, is a much more recent development.{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=45–59}}
Assigning phonetic values to the finals has proved more difficult, as many of the distinctions reflected in the ''Qieyun'' have been lost over time. Karlgren proposed that type B finals contained a [[palatal approximant|palatal medial]] {{IPA|/j/}}, a position that is still accepted by most scholars. However Pulleyblank, noting the use of these syllables in the transcription of foreign words without such a medial, claims the medial developed later. A [[labio-velar approximant|labiovelar medial]] {{IPA|/w/}} is also widely accepted, with some syllables having both medials. The codas are believed to reflect those of many modern varieties, namely the glides {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}}, nasals {{IPA|/m/}}, {{IPA|/n/}} and {{IPA|/ŋ/}} and corresponding stops {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/k/}}. Some authors argue that the placement of the first four rhyme groups in the ''Qieyun'' suggests that they had distinct codas, reconstructed as [[labialized velar consonant|labiovelar]]s {{IPA|/ŋʷ/}} and {{IPA|/kʷ/}}. Most reconstructions posit a large number of vowels to distinguish the many ''Qieyun'' rhyme classes that occur with some codas, but the number and the values assigned vary widely.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=36–39}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=61–63, 70–71}}
The Chinese linguist [[Li Rong (linguist)|Li Rong]] published a study of the early edition of the ''Qieyun'' found in 1947, showing that the expanded dictionaries had preserved the phonological structure of the ''Qieyun'' intact, except for a merger of initials /dʐ/ and /ʐ/. For example, although the number of rhyme groups increased from 193 in the earlier dictionary to 206 in the ''Guangyun'', the differences are limited to splitting rhyme groups based on the presence or absence of a medial glide [[Labio-velar approximant|{{IPA|/w/}}]].{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=24–27}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=38–40}}{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1984|pp=135–136}}
However the preface of the recovered ''Qieyun'' suggests that it represented a compromise between northern and southern reading pronunciations.{{efn|For translations of the ''Qieyun'' preface, see {{harvtxt|Baxter|1992}}, pp. 35–36 and {{harvtxt|Ramsey|1989}}, pp. 116–117.}} Most linguists now believe that no single dialect contained all the distinctions recorded, but that each distinction did occur somewhere.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=24–25}}{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=35–38}} For example, the ''Qieyun'' distinguished three rhyme groups 支, 脂 and 之 (all pronounced ''zhī'' in modern Chinese), although 支 and 脂 were not distinguished in parts of the north, while 脂 and 之 rhymed in the south. The three groups are treated as ''tongyong'' in the ''Guangyun'' and have merged in all modern varieties.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1998|pp=203–204}} Although Karlgren's identification of the ''Qieyun'' system with a Sui-Tang standard is no longer accepted, the fact that it contains more distinctions than any single contemporary form of speech means that it retains more information about earlier stages of the language, and is a major component in the reconstruction of [[Old Chinese phonology]].{{sfnp|Baxter|1992|pp=37–38}}
==''Pingshui'' rhyme categories== From early in the Tang dynasty, candidates in the [[imperial examination]] were required to compose [[Chinese poetry|poetry]] and [[Fu (poetry)|rhymed prose]] in conformance with the rhyme categories of the ''Qieyun''. However, the fine distinctions made by the ''Qieyun'' were found overly restrictive by poets, and [[Xu Jingzong]] and others suggested more relaxed rhyming rules.{{sfnp|Pulleyblank|1984|p=139}} The ''Píngshuǐ'' (平水) system of 106 rhyme groups, first codified during the [[Jin dynasty (1115–1234)|Jin dynasty]], eventually became the prescribed system for the imperial examination. It became the standard for official rhyme books, and was also used as the classification system for such reference works as the ''[[Peiwen Yunfu]]''.{{sfnp|Branner|1999|p=87}}{{sfnp|Yong|Peng|2008|p=324}}
The ''Píngshuǐ'' rhyme groups are the same as the ''tóngyòng'' groups of the ''Guangyun'', with a few exceptions:{{sfnp|Branner|1999|p=87}} * The 廢 ''fèi'' group is merged with 隊 ''duì''.{{sfnp|Branner|1999|p=92}} * The rising and departing tone groups corresponding to 蒸 ''zhēng'' were merged into the 迥 ''jiǒng'' and 徑 ''jìng'' groups. * The groups 嚴 ''yán'' and 凡 ''fán'', which were ''tóngyòng'' in the ''Guangyun'', and in complementary distribution, were split between the two preceding ''tóngyòng'' groups.{{sfnp|Branner|1999|pp=106–107}}
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto;" |+ ''Pingshui'' rhyme groups by tone{{sfnp|Creamer|1991|p=2609}} ! 平 level !! 上 rising !! 去 departing !! 入 entering |- | 東 ''dōng'' || 董 ''dǒng'' || 送 ''sòng'' || 屋 ''wū'' |- | 冬 ''dōng'' || 腫 ''zhǒng'' || 宋 ''sòng'' || 沃 ''wò'' |- | 江 ''jiāng'' || 講 ''jiǎng'' || 絳 ''jiàng'' || 覺 ''jué'' |- | 支 ''zhī'' || 紙 ''zhǐ'' || 寘 ''zhì'' || |- | 微 ''wēi'' || 尾 ''wěi'' || 未 ''wèi'' || |- | 魚 ''yú'' || 語 ''yǔ'' || 御 ''yù'' || |- | 虞 ''yú'' || 麌 ''yǔ'' || 遇 ''yù'' || |- | 齊 ''qí'' || 薺 ''jì'' || 霽 ''jì'' || |- | || || 泰 ''tài'' || |- | 佳 ''jiā'' || 蟹 ''xiè'' || 卦 ''guà'' || |- | 灰 ''huī'' || 賄 ''huì'' || 隊 ''duì'' || |- | 真 ''zhēn'' || 軫 ''zhěn'' || 震 ''zhèn'' || 質 ''zhì'' |- | 文 ''wén'' || 吻 ''wěn'' || 問 ''wèn'' || 物 ''wù'' |- | 元 ''yuán'' || 阮 ''ruǎn'' || 願 ''yuàn'' || 月 ''yuè'' |- | 寒 ''hán'' || 旱 ''hàn'' || 翰 ''hàn'' || 曷 ''hé'' |- | 刪 ''shān'' || 潸 ''shān'' || 諫 ''jiàn'' || 鎋 ''xiá'' |- | 先 ''xiān'' || 銑 ''xiǎn'' || 霰 ''xiàn'' || 屑 ''xiè'' |- | 蕭 ''xiāo'' || 篠 ''xiǎo'' || 嘯 ''xiào'' || |- | 肴 ''yáo'' || 巧 ''qiǎo'' || 效 ''xiào'' || |- | 豪 ''háo'' || 晧 ''hào'' || 號 ''hào'' || |- | 歌 ''gē'' || 哿 ''gě'' || 箇 ''gè'' || |- | 麻 ''má'' || 馬 ''mǎ'' || 禡 ''mà'' || |- | 陽 ''yáng'' || 養 ''yǎng'' || 漾 ''yàng'' || 藥 ''yào'' |- | 庚 ''gēng'' || 梗 ''gěng'' || 映 ''yìng'' || 陌 ''mò'' |- | 青 ''qīng'' || 迥 ''jiǒng'' || 徑 ''jìng'' || 錫 ''xī'' |- | 蒸 ''zhēng'' || || || 職 ''zhí'' |- | 尤 ''yóu'' || 有 ''yǒu'' || 宥 ''yòu'' || |- | 侵 ''qīn'' || 寑 ''qǐn'' || 沁 ''qìn'' || 緝 ''qì'' |- | 覃 ''tán'' || 感 ''gǎn'' || 勘 ''kàn'' || 合 ''hé'' |- | 鹽 ''yán'' || 琰 ''yǎn'' || 豔 ''yàn'' || 葉 ''yè'' |- | 咸 ''xián'' || 豏 ''xiàn'' || 陷 ''xiàn'' || 洽 ''qià'' |}
[[Yan Zhengqing]]'s ''[[Yunhai jingyuan]]'' (c. 780) was the first rime dictionary of multisyllabic words rather than single characters.{{sfnp|Yong|Peng|2008|p=226}} Though no longer extant, it served as the model for a series of encyclopedic dictionaries of literary words and phrases organized by ''Píngshuǐ'' rhyme groups, culminating in the ''[[Peiwen Yunfu]]'' (1711).{{sfnp|Yong|Peng|2008|pp=324, 332–333}}
==Vernacular dictionaries== [[File:Zhongyuan Yinyun 侵尋 rhyme group.png|thumb|right|upright=1.5|''Zhongyuan Yinyun'' rhyme group 侵尋 (-im, -əm), divided into four tones]] A side-effect of foreign rule of northern China between the 10th and 14th centuries was a weakening of many of the old traditions. New genres of vernacular literature such as the ''[[Qu (poetry)|qu]]'' and ''[[Chinese Sanqu poetry|sanqu]]'' poetry appeared, as well as the ''[[Zhongyuan Yinyun]]'', created by Zhōu Déqīng (周德清) in 1324 as a guide to the rhyming conventions of ''qu''. The ''Zhongyuan Yinyun'' was a radical departure from the rhyme table tradition, with the entries grouped into 19 rhyme classes each identified by a pair of exemplary characters. These rhyme classes combined rhymes from different tones, whose parallelism was implicit in the ordered of the ''Guangyun'' ryhmes. The rhyme classes are subdivided by tone and then into groups of homophones, with no other indication of pronunciation. The dictionary reflects [[Old Mandarin|contemporaneous northern speech]], with the even tone divided in upper and lower tones, and the loss of the Middle Chinese final stops.{{sfnp|Norman|1988|pp=49–50}} Such syllables, formerly grouped in the entering tone, are distributed between the other tones, but placed after the other syllables with labels such as 入聲作去聲 (''rùshēng zuò qùshēng'' "entering tone makes departing tone").{{sfnp|Yong|Peng|2008|p=252}}
The early Ming dictionary ''Yùnluè yìtōng'' (韻略易通) by Lan Mao was based on the ''Zhongyuan Yinyun'', but arranged the homophone groups according to a fixed order of initials, which were listed in a mnemonic poem in the ''[[ci (poetry)|ci]]'' form.{{sfnp|Yong|Peng|2008|p=272}}{{sfnp|Li|1993|p=30}} However, there could still be multiple homophone groups under a given rhyme group, tone and initial, as medial glides were not considered part of the rhyme. Further innovations are found in a rime dictionary from the late 16th century describing the [[Fuzhou dialect]], which is preserved, together with a later redaction, in the ''[[Qi Lin Bayin]]''. This work enumerates the finals of the dialect, differentiated by both medial and rhyme, and classifies each homophone group uniquely by final, initial and tone. Both finals and initials are listed in ''ci'' poems.{{sfnp|Li|1993|pp=30–34}}
==Tangut== [[File:Sea of Characters Level Tone folio 53.jpg|thumb|right|''Sea of Characters'', level tone folio 53]] [[Tangut language|Tangut]] was the language of the [[Western Xia]] state (1038–1227), centred on the area of modern [[Gansu]]. The language had been extinct for four centuries when an extensive corpus of documents in the logographic [[Tangut script]] were discovered in the early 20th century. One of the sources used to reconstruct the Tangut language is the ''Sea of Characters'' [[File:LFW2008 4797.png|16px]][[File:LFW2008 0661.png|16px]] ({{zh|c=文海|p=Wénhǎi}}), a rhyme dictionary written entirely in Tangut, but with the same structure as the Chinese dictionaries. The dictionary consists of one volume each for the Tangut level and rising tones, with a third volume of "mixed category" characters, whose significance is unclear. As with the Chinese dictionaries, each volume is divided into rhymes, and then into homophone groups separated by a small circle. The pronunciation of the first Tangut character in each homophone group is given by a ''fanqie'' formula using a pair of Tangut characters. Mikhail Sofronov applied Chen Li's method to these ''fanqie'' to construct the system of Tangut initials and finals.{{sfnp|Jacques|2016}}
